'''Štěpánka Haničincová''' (née Hubáčková; 30 September 1931 – 27 October 1999) was a Czechoslovak actress, [[screenwriter]], [[dramaturge]] and children's television presenter.

==Personal life==
She was born '''Štěpánka Hubáčková''' in [[Kvíčovice]] on 30 September 1931. Her father was a [[shoemaker]].<ref name=ct>{{cite web|url=http://www.ceskatelevize.cz/_archiv/99/teac/archiv/99/11/hanicincova.html|title=štìpánka hanièincová|language=Czech|work=Česká televize|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> She spent her early childhood in the town of [[Heřmanův Městec]],<ref name=ctdoc>{{cite web|url=http://www.ceskatelevize.cz/porady/10123383458-pribehy-slavnych/403235100111003-stepanka-tezsi-zivot-je-lepsi/|title=Příběhy slavných Štěpánka: "Těžší život je lepší"|language=Czech|work=Česká televize|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> before her parents divorced and she moved with her mother to [[Děčín]].<ref name=ct/>

She was the first wife of actor [[Petr Haničinec]], whom she met at the [[Faculty of Theatre (Prague)|Faculty of Theatre in Prague]] where they both studied.<ref name=aha>{{cite web|url=http://www.ahaonline.cz/clanek/zhave-drby/18477/herec-petr-hanicinec-77-se-zivotem-se-pral-od-zacatku.html|title=Herec Petr Haničinec (†77) - Se životem se pral od začátku|trans-title=Actor Peter Haničinec († 77) - Life was a fight from the beginning|date=11 November 2007|work=AhaOnline.com|accessdate=26 April 2014}}</ref> The couple had one child, a daughter named Alexandra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kultura.idnes.cz/zemrel-herec-petr-hanicinec-df7-/divadlo.aspx?c=A071107_084409_divadlo_miz|title=Zemřel herec Petr Haničinec|language=Czech|work=Mladá fronta DNES|date=7 November 2007|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> Her second husband was director [[Jan Valášek]] who died in 1968 and her last husband was the actor [[Jan Přeučil]]. She had a total of two children.<ref name=ct/>

==Career==
Haničincová was a children's television presenter on Czech TV.<ref name=celeb/> Before making her television debut she took part in [[amateur theatre]].<ref name=ct/> She was first broadcast in 1953.<ref name=ct/> Her other television roles included being an actress, screenwriter and dramaturge.<ref name=tyty>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio.cz/cz/rubrika/bulletin/zpravy-pondeli-08-unora-1999|title=Zprávy pondělí, 08. února 1999|trans-title=News Monday 8 February 1999|language=Czech|work=Radio Prague|date=8 February 1999|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> One of the films she appeared in, ''[[Honzíkova cesta]]'', won a silver medal at the [[Venice Film Festival]].<ref>[http://az-europe.eu/en/3x-children-s-film-p134791/e 3 films], az-europe.eu, retrieved 25 April 2014</ref> Haničincová was voted into the ''{{lang|cs|TýTý}}'' Hall of Fame at the annual ''{{lang|cs|TýTý}}'' television awards in February 1999, in recognition of her contribution to television in her nation.<ref name=tyty/>

Haničincová died at the age of 68 in [[Prague]] in October 1999,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radio.cz/cz/rubrika/bulletin/zpravy-patek-29-rijna-1999|title=Zprávy pátek, 29. října 1999|trans-title=News Friday 29 October 1999|language=Czech|work=Radio Prague|date=29 October 1999|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> following a fall where she hit her head on a radiator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brnensky.denik.cz/kultura_region/pohadkari-navrati-do-detstvi-sokovou-terapii-20131112.html|title=Pohádkáři navrátí do dětství šokovou terapií|language=Czech|work=Deník|date=13 November 2013|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> Her death was said to be linked to alcohol.<ref name=celeb>[http://www.alkoholik.cz/zavislost/celebrity_a_alkohol/celebrity_slavne_osobnosti_a_alkohol_alkoholismus.html Celebities and alcohol], alkoholik.cz, retrieved 24 April 2014</ref> Haničinec described her as "an intelligent and benevolent lady".<ref name=aha/> Haničincová's life story was the subject of a 2003 television documentary broadcast by state television network [[Česká televize]].<ref name=ctdoc/>

